One of the first things I did when I moved into this house a couple years ago was get 3 bird feeders. I put 2 in the backyard and this clear one on my bedroom door. 

My fascination with birds comes from long ago and it’s mainly because of my grandad. He was obsessed with birds and always had lots of them; he loved to watch them and hear them sing. He would point out their beautiful colors and the different species. He knew his bird game, and after he passed away a few years ago, I started to appreciate even more the magic message behind the birds that every now and then come to my window.

Sitting in my bed and having the opportunity to see them free, and this close has been truly special. Not only do they remind me of Tony (my grampa) who meant the world to me, but they also remind me of the beauty there is in the little things. They remind me that today is all we have. They remind me that I don’t need a lot to be happy, just enough to be fulfilled. 

Every time a bird comes this close, I feel like my grampa is trying to send me a message:
Stop and appreciate the beauty around you; take a break and breath in. Be grateful for the love you have. Give back. Be kind to others and do your best. Show up for your family and friends. Be present in the moment. Be your best version.

Today Tony would have turned 91. The sky is celebrating and so am as I watch all these birds come to my window reminding me how lucky I am ❤️

Are you feeling 😞, 🙂 or 😡 today? This painting wall in our classes this week was the perfect opportunity to open up conversations about emotions and feelings, plus the little and big kids LOVED covering them in paint!

Finding moments to create just for the sake of having some time for me, has been very challenging lately. 

This quick exercise today with felt and a black paper in the background was very relaxing and refreshing. 15 minutes of no expectations other than sitting still, cutting and arranging pieces over the paper was a sweet reminder that I need to find more time to PLAY and enjoy my very own creative process❤️

Playing together. Creating and connecting. Building community and providing the environment for many situations to unfold. The calm and the storm. The quiet and the noisy. The mellow and the feisty. But foremost the REAL. 

The collaboration and the conflict. The sharing and the “mine”. The frustration and the joy. The “I can do this” and the “this is too hard”. The hugging and the hitting. 

Real life dynamics that present themselves every week as an opportunity to plant seeds of love, forgiveness, self regulation, compassion, respect, mindfulness, conscious discipline, tolerance and empathy among many others.

This is Art Playgroup. We celebrate the good and we learn from the challenging little moments.  We grow together as parents, as teachers, as children and as a community. 

Thank you for being a part of it all❤️

During the pandemic we did a lot of fishing. It got us out of our small condo, and living in Miami it was easy to find good fishing spots anywhere. The boys loved it and learned a new skill in these odd times.

But then we never did it again; we got caught up in our regular nonstop routines and fishing was no longer a part of our plans.

So reconnecting with it this weekend was fun. It reminded me of the power of these quiet slow moments where we can savor the present. It reminded me of my grampa and my dad who were fisherman’s. We got to hang out as a family and spent a couple hours just staring at the ocean. Waiting for it. And we sure waited. With nothing but uncertainty. 

Simple little moments are my favorite. I don’t need far away fancy trips (as a matter of fact I confess planning these makes me anxious); all I need to fill my cup is quality time with the people I love. And if it’s near the water even better🙂

Have you tried fishing with kids? Yay or nay?

🌈STAY STRONG, THERE’S A RAINBOW AFTER EVERY STORM🌈

I started making these little rainbows out of @sculpey_official during the pandemic. It became a therapy for me. Whenever I felt anxious and overwhelmed I made rainbows. So I made a LOT of them…I gifted them to friends and family and I felt these little colorful pieces spread some hope among such a heavy and uncertain time.

I originally started making them inspired by the amazing @creatiivenatiive and after a couple of years of making none at all, today it felt nice to sit down for a couple hours and make a few.❤️

Note to self: PLAY MORE 🪷
#plasticineart 

Finding time through the week to connect more with my creative process. It’s not easy but so necessary. And when I MAKE something, not for others, not with an objective in mind, but with the sole purpose of enjoying the process, it feels so good. 

I encourage you to find little moments to PLAY more. Whatever Play looks like to you. For me, it’s making art; but for you, it might be something completely different. Find it. Embrace it. And never let go. 

PLAY MORE.

When Manolo asked me if he could burn his math book from this past year I hesitated for a few seconds but ended up saying YES.  Let me add on my behalf that I did ask first if he was sure he didn’t want to keep it to practice during the summer. He rolled his eyes. Of course 🙄 

This is just an example of those opportunities that may come up where you can say yes more. I know it can be hard sometimes, going out of our comfort zone, having to clean up a mess, trusting our child and letting them take lead. I get it. 

Saying yes more allows us to raise creative children as they understand the world in a better way and try out new things, knowing that their parents will frequently agree to their ideas. Of course it all depends on each specific situation, but I encourage you today to say yes to something out of your comfort zone. Trust your child’s process and build up their confidence by letting them take initiative; walk next to them and observe as it all unfolds organically. You will feel empowered too as you empower them🔥

*no living beings were harmed in the making of this fire. Only a 4th grade math book. 😳

3 years ago today, our life changed forever. Junior arrived and our days were never the same❤️ 

We were amidst of the pandemic. Uncertain and weird times. I had been struggling with anxiety and panic disorder and all I wanted for my birthday was a puppy. When I saw Junior it was love at first sight. He was the one for me; the perfect dog for our family. I just felt it.

He became my sidekick. A huge emotional support in my journey towards coping with the ugly feelings I was experimenting. Every time I turned he was there, by my side. When I felt a knot in my chest, he was there. When I was happy he was there. When I felt like I couldn’t breathe, he was there. Always there. Nothing compares to the unconditional love of a dog.

Mental health is a constant work in progress. 23+ years in it for me… A permanent quest in the ongoing journey towards healing and becoming a better person. One day at a time. Always with my people and 🐶 by my side.

Junior: thank you for coming to complete us! 
We love you always forever. ❤️

Many of you probably didn’t know that I worked in Public relations and entertainment for about 8 years before starting Redviolet. I made good money and I was ok at it, but I was not happy. I always felt happier when I was painting, crafting or overall creating something (which I never stopped doing). Deep inside I knew where my passion and my heart would truly shine, but I was afraid to embark on a different and unknown journey. I felt secure knowing I had a paycheck +benefits every month working a job that did not fulfill me. It was my comfort zone. And damn was it hard to leave it. I had to get fired to realize there was something else out there for me.

Like Mark Twain said: “Find a job you enjoy doing, and you will never have to work a day in your life.”

Well, after years of trial and error, mistakes, achievements  challenges and lots of learning, I can say not working a day in my life with Redviolet Studio has been the best job I’ve ever had. No pun intended. 🙂

Children are biologically designed to EDUCATE THEMSELVES! 

This is what had me start REDVIOLET STUDIO 10 years ago. This strong belief that a child doesn’t need to be told what to do; he needs to be provided with the right environment and stimulus to learn, explore and discover through play. Organic child led play. 

The moment I had my first child and started shopping for the right school for him; that’s when it all came to me. Visiting some preschool’s where it just didn’t seem right; at least not for me or my kids. That’s when I started learning more and more about this way of seeing childhood, of embracing it and respecting it. No rush. No specific or set agenda. 

In the end you do you. Do whatever seems right and appropriate for your child and your family. 

For me, this is home. This is what feels right. And this is what we provide in our #artplaygroup sessions for our #earlychildhood groups❤️

ART is not a luxury, it’s a necessity. 

You don’t need permission to be creative. Art should be a part of everyone’s life, regardless of age, gender, upbringing, class, race etc.  It should be in every curriculum, household and in everyday life.

You don’t have to be an art teacher, a student or a full time artist to experiment and create. Art is everywhere. Creativity is one of the most powerful skills we can have. We are all born with it in different ways. Water it. Give it some light and food. Cuddle and embrace it. And moreover, pass it on to your kids. Raise them to know Art and creativity are not a luxury but a necessity.

💦WATER! A favorite. Always! 💦
